contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:14.777 --> 01:17.746
- Hey. Bob, what's up?
- <i>Hi. Listen.</i>

01:17.748 --> 01:21.149
<i>According to an unconfirmed
report, David Wallace is dead.</i>

01:21.151 --> 01:24.419
What? No. No, no, no.

01:24.421 --> 01:28.056
No, It must be some sort of a
college prank or something.

01:28.058 --> 01:33.127
<i>Well, I thought if anybody knew whether
it was true or not, it'd be you.</i>

01:36.866 --> 01:40.336
<i>Now a remembrance of writer
David Foster Wallace.</i>

01:40.338 --> 01:44.739
<i>He was found dead, an apparent
suicide, on Friday night.</i>

01:44.741 --> 01:47.809
<i>Wallace's novel,</i> Infinite
Jest, <i>brought him fame...</i>

01:47.811 --> 01:49.110
and a wide audience.

01:49.112 --> 01:51.678
Writer David Lipsky
has this appreciation.

01:54.984 --> 01:59.286
"To read David Foster Wallace was
to feel your eyelids pulled open."

02:00.821 --> 02:04.624
<i>Some writers specialize in the
'away from home' experience.</i>

02:04.626 --> 02:08.727
<i>They have safaried, eaten
across Italy, covered a war.</i>

02:10.229 --> 02:13.232
<i>Wallace offered his alive self,</i>

02:13.234 --> 02:15.234
<i>cutting through
our sleepy aquarium,</i>

02:15.236 --> 02:19.205
<i>our standard TV, stores,
political campaigns.</i>

02:21.474 --> 02:25.110
<i>Writers who can do this...
like Salinger and Fitzgerald...</i>

02:25.112 --> 02:27.880
<i>forge an unbreakable bond
with readers.</i>

02:27.882 --> 02:32.016
<i>You didn't slip into the books
looking for a story, information,</i>

02:32.018 --> 02:35.053
<i>but for a particular
experience...</i>

02:35.055 --> 02:38.222
<i>the sensation,
for a certain number of pages,</i>

02:38.224 --> 02:41.492
<i>"of being David Foster Wallace."</i>

02:45.897 --> 02:49.132
<i>If anything, there was
a conscious attempt...</i>

02:49.134 --> 02:51.701
<i>to not give overt direction,</i>

02:51.703 --> 02:54.304
<i>although, of course,
you end up becoming yourself.</i>

02:55.673 --> 02:57.640
<i>Did they want you
to be a writer or no?</i>

02:57.642 --> 02:59.909
<i>No. I was gonna be... The big
thing, when I was little...</i>

02:59.911 --> 03:02.478
<i>I was... I was, like, a
really serious jock. Really?</i>

03:02.480 --> 03:04.547
<i>Yeah. I played
citywide football as a kid.</i>

03:04.549 --> 03:07.616
<i>I was really big,
really strong as a kid.</i>

03:07.618 --> 03:10.987
<i>And then for four or five years, I was
gonna be, like, a pro tennis player.</i>

03:10.989 --> 03:12.922
<i>That was my great dream.</i>

03:12.924 --> 03:14.623
<i>Reading was just
this kind of fun,</i>

03:14.625 --> 03:17.326
<i>sort of weird thing
that I did on the side.</i>

03:26.302 --> 03:28.003
"I didn't understand SoHo..."

03:28.005 --> 03:32.206
the warehouses, the old
buildings, the cobbled streets.

03:32.208 --> 03:36.143
It wasn't the Upper East Side,
and it was dirty.

03:37.712 --> 03:39.212
I felt marooned.

03:39.214 --> 03:42.950
Our mother had taken us off the track
of the nice life we'd been on.

03:42.952 --> 03:46.054
She'd moored us in a creepy cul-de-sac
with her art-world friends.

03:46.056 --> 03:48.756
<i>None of the kids in my school
had parents in the art world.</i>

03:48.758 --> 03:50.657
<i>It made me feel different,</i>

03:50.659 --> 03:52.593
<i>like there was something
I had to cover up."</i>

03:54.296 --> 03:56.229
It was great.
Sorry I missed it.

03:56.231 --> 03:58.498
Don't worry about it.

03:58.500 --> 04:00.766
Hey. I heard you got
that <i> Rolling Stone</i> job.

04:00.768 --> 04:03.770
We'll see. I'm sort of on probation.
Good luck.

04:03.772 --> 04:06.372
Did you see Kirn's review
in <i> New York</i> magazine?

04:06.374 --> 04:08.640
The guy's been
fuckin' canonized.

04:08.642 --> 04:09.875
Sorry. Who's this?

04:09.877 --> 04:11.877
David Foster Wallace.

04:11.879 --> 04:14.346
"Next year's book awards have been
decided." Can you believe this?

04:14.348 --> 04:17.850
"The plaques and citations can now be
put into escrow." It's unbelievable.

04:17.851 --> 04:20.252
"With <i> Infinite Jest,</i>
by David Foster Wallace,

04:20.254 --> 04:24.723
a plutonium-dense, satirical quiz-kid opus
that runs to almost a thousand"... What?

04:24.725 --> 04:27.760
"A thousand pages,
not including footnotes,"

04:27.762 --> 04:29.561
the competition
has been obliterated.

04:29.563 --> 04:32.163
It's as though Paul Bunyan
had joined the NFL...

04:32.165 --> 04:34.166
or Wittgenstein
had gone onto <i> Jeopardy!.</i>

04:34.168 --> 04:37.335
"The novel is that colossally disruptive
and that spectacularly good."

04:37.337 --> 04:39.705
That's the fucking
opening paragraph.

04:39.707 --> 04:42.540
What if it actually
is that good?

04:43.542 --> 04:46.278
You might just have to read it.

04:57.557 --> 04:58.891
Shit.

04:58.893 --> 05:00.626
Good piece. Thanks a lot.

05:02.095 --> 05:03.830
Solid piece. I'm fine with it.

05:03.832 --> 05:06.033
But you gotta clear it
with Legal, okay?

05:08.267 --> 05:10.869
How many times have we interviewed
a writer in the last 10 years?

05:10.871 --> 05:13.705
Take a guess.

05:13.707 --> 05:15.039
Uh, how many?

05:15.041 --> 05:17.575
Zero. I checked.

05:17.577 --> 05:19.697
Maybe because <i> Rolling Stone</i>
doesn't interview writers.

05:20.678 --> 05:23.247
There hasn't been a writer
like this. Okay?

05:23.249 --> 05:26.650
Once in a generation maybe.
Hemingway, Pynchon.

05:26.652 --> 05:29.153
Let me have this story.
What story?

05:29.155 --> 05:32.222
He's finishing up a book tour,
and I want to go with him.

05:32.224 --> 05:33.857
That's not a story.

05:33.859 --> 05:37.393
He teaches at some small state
university somewhere in Illinois.

05:37.395 --> 05:39.361
Please, Bob. Send me there.

05:39.363 --> 05:43.332
This is the sort of stuff I should be
doing, not 500 words on boy bands.

05:44.967 --> 05:46.902
Talk to Jann.

05:59.550 --> 06:01.950
There better be a story there.

06:04.921 --> 06:07.422
There will be. There better.

07:39.492 --> 07:42.527
David, hi. It's David Lipsky.
<i>Where are you?</i>

07:42.529 --> 07:44.896
I think I may have made
a wrong turn somewhere.

07:44.898 --> 07:47.399
Let's see. I am on
County Highway 29...

07:47.401 --> 07:50.001
just across
from the Circus Video.

07:50.003 --> 07:51.937
<i>How'd you get this number?</i>

07:51.939 --> 07:55.640
Your publicist sent it
in her e-mail, just in case.

07:55.642 --> 07:58.777
<i>You'd do me a favor
by losing it.</i>

08:50.168 --> 08:52.936
Stay. Be calm. Be calm. Stay.

08:55.739 --> 08:58.241
Hey. You made it. Yeah.

08:58.243 --> 08:59.842
Dave. Dave Wallace.

08:59.844 --> 09:02.444
David Lipsky. Hi.
It's a pleasure.

09:02.446 --> 09:04.613
Likewise.

09:04.615 --> 09:07.048
Um, I'm sorry about
the, uh... the phone call.

09:07.050 --> 09:08.215
No, you're fine.

09:08.217 --> 09:12.119
It was 95% joke.
Right, right. Yeah.

09:12.121 --> 09:15.388
Sorry in advance about the dogs.
They'll be slobbering all over you.

09:15.390 --> 09:17.157
I don't mind at all.
I love dogs.

09:17.159 --> 09:20.293
Oh, yeah? You haven't met these guys yet.
No, I love 'em.

09:20.295 --> 09:23.697
Let's, uh... Oh, Jesus. Let's get inside.
It's cold.

09:23.699 --> 09:26.499
Boys. Get in there.
Thanks a lot.

09:26.501 --> 09:28.768
Ooh. Come on. Come on, buddy.

09:28.770 --> 09:30.903
Wait. I'm very glad to meet you too.
Good dog.

09:30.905 --> 09:33.506
Who's that? Oh, that's Jeeves.

09:33.508 --> 09:36.141
Hi. Yeah, that's
the Jeeve-meister.

09:36.143 --> 09:38.476
I got him 'cause he was so ugly.
Nobody else wanted him.

09:38.478 --> 09:40.145
Now he's, like,
a cover girl dog.

09:40.147 --> 09:42.480
And that's Drone.
That's my provisional dog.

09:42.482 --> 09:44.915
Why? Why provisional?

09:44.917 --> 09:47.285
He just showed up one day while
Jeeves and I were out jogging.

09:47.287 --> 09:49.887
The rest is history.

09:49.889 --> 09:52.757
I feel like I should
offer you tea or something.

09:52.759 --> 09:55.719
Yeah. Yeah, thanks. That'd be great.
Yeah? Okay.

10:13.279 --> 10:15.581
Nice view.

10:15.583 --> 10:18.983
Thank you. I can't
take credit for it.

10:18.985 --> 10:20.851
Huh.

10:23.555 --> 10:27.124
So, um, have you
always been unlisted?

10:28.427 --> 10:31.462
I had to do that recently. It
was getting kind of crazy.

10:31.464 --> 10:33.932
Oh. Because of...
Because of fans.

10:33.934 --> 10:36.467
I don't know if "fan" is
exactly the right word.

10:36.469 --> 10:40.138
I think what happened was I had forgotten to
tell my parents not to give my number out.

10:40.140 --> 10:42.707
So it was people who had
tracked my parents down.

10:42.709 --> 10:45.911
I have this terrible problem. I really
hate to hurt people's feelings.

10:45.913 --> 10:49.080
Mmm, right. So I did
somethin' kind of cowardly.

10:49.082 --> 10:53.118
No. I don't think unlisting your
number is cowardly. Kind of is.

10:53.120 --> 10:55.887
I changed my number so these
folks couldn't find me anymore.

10:55.889 --> 10:57.121
Right.

10:57.123 --> 10:59.557
There was this computer
operator from Vancouver.

10:59.559 --> 11:01.091
He was living in a
basement or something.

11:01.093 --> 11:04.894
I found him very moving. He was
in terrible, terrible pain.

11:04.896 --> 11:06.829
What did he want from you?

11:06.831 --> 11:09.799
It's unclear. And when I
would, sorta like, ask him,

11:09.801 --> 11:12.968
that's when he would get angry,
and then it got scary.

11:12.970 --> 11:16.338
Right. What-What is this?
Who's the artist?

11:17.673 --> 11:20.241
That's my friend's daughter.
Calls me chicken head.

11:20.243 --> 11:21.977
I call her chicken head.

11:21.979 --> 11:24.612
It's her latest salvo
in the war.

11:24.614 --> 11:27.849
Um, that's funny.
Would you mind if I...

11:27.851 --> 11:30.384
No. Do what you gotta do.
Thank you.

11:37.559 --> 11:42.429
Listen, before we start putting stuff
on tape, I need to ask you something.

11:42.431 --> 11:46.033
I need to know that anything that I
say five minutes later not to put in,

11:46.035 --> 11:48.301
that you're not
gonna put it in.

11:48.935 --> 11:50.936
Absolutely.

11:50.938 --> 11:54.040
Just given my level of fatigue
and my fuckup quotient lately,

11:54.042 --> 11:57.411
it's the only way I can see doin'
it and not... not going crazy.

11:57.413 --> 11:59.379
No. I completely understand.

12:01.349 --> 12:04.031
It's right back on, huh? Mmm.

12:05.118 --> 12:07.752
Uh, you agreed
to the interview.

12:13.792 --> 12:15.927
So this is your road, huh?

12:15.929 --> 12:17.762
Yeah, this is my road.

12:17.764 --> 12:20.464
You're gonna have to tell me where to turn.
I'm used to a grid system.

12:20.466 --> 12:22.300
This is all new
territory for me.

12:22.302 --> 12:25.436
Fair enough. You just go
straight for about a mile.

12:25.438 --> 12:27.539
There'll be signs for the
school on the right.

12:27.541 --> 12:30.308
Got it. Do you like
teaching there?

12:30.310 --> 12:33.645
I do. Yeah, very much.
Which is what's so fucked.

12:33.647 --> 12:36.481
I feel so bad for these kids.
Why do you feel bad for them?

12:36.483 --> 12:38.983
They have the greatest writing
teacher in the world.

12:38.985 --> 12:42.120
If I was there, maybe.
The whole fuss...

12:42.122 --> 12:43.688
it's taken me out of school
for the past two weeks.

12:43.690 --> 12:45.424
And we gotta leave
again tomorrow.

12:45.426 --> 12:48.093
We gotta be up at the crack
of dawn to go to the airport.

12:48.095 --> 12:51.196
Oh, shit. Do we really? That's
what you signed on for, man.

12:51.198 --> 12:53.532
You're welcome to stick around and
write an article about my dogs.

12:53.534 --> 12:56.868
No, that's just fine. Might be
more interesting. I promise you.

12:56.870 --> 12:59.938
Do yourself a favor. Don't
expect any fireworks in there.

12:59.940 --> 13:01.806
I'm sure you're gonna
be just fine.

13:01.808 --> 13:04.009
Campus-romance story.

13:04.011 --> 13:06.978
Ah! I gotta tell you guys,

13:06.980 --> 13:10.115
the average citizen is not gonna
find it that interesting.

13:10.117 --> 13:12.717
The great dread of creative
writing professors?

13:12.719 --> 13:17.355
"Their eyes met over the keg."

13:17.357 --> 13:19.757
I just want my narrator to be
funny and smart, you know?

13:19.759 --> 13:21.225
I know, I know. I get it.

13:21.227 --> 13:23.528
You want your narrator
to be funny and smart.

13:23.530 --> 13:25.096
Here's a tip.

13:25.098 --> 13:27.999
Have him say funny, smart things
some of the time.

13:28.001 --> 13:29.166
Thank you.

13:29.168 --> 13:30.700
You did a good job. Thank you.

13:30.702 --> 13:33.637
Um, all right, who's next?
Melissa.

13:33.639 --> 13:36.006
I'm normally a much better
teacher than that, I swear.

13:36.008 --> 13:38.575
I thought you were great and
that they obviously love you.

13:38.577 --> 13:39.944
Oh, yeah? Do you think?

13:39.946 --> 13:42.313
Yeah, come on,
you know they do.

13:42.315 --> 13:43.914
You hungry?

13:47.219 --> 13:48.852
<i>And what can I
get you to drink?</i>

13:48.854 --> 13:52.990
I'll just have, like, a
giant Diet Rite, please.

13:52.992 --> 13:54.925
You know what,
I'll have the same thing.

13:54.927 --> 13:58.129
I'll be right back with your pop.
Thanks, man.

13:59.598 --> 14:02.098
Oh. Uh, can I, uh...

14:03.968 --> 14:07.103
Do you mind if I... One second.

14:08.606 --> 14:12.107
Uh...

14:13.809 --> 14:15.944
You don't drink.

14:19.748 --> 14:21.549
Is that a question to me?

14:21.551 --> 14:23.817
No. No, it's an observation.

14:23.819 --> 14:27.221
Ah, I see. No, I know.
No, I do not drink.

14:27.223 --> 14:29.456
You can order whatever you want though.
Go right ahead.

14:29.458 --> 14:30.857
No, no. That's fine.

14:30.859 --> 14:33.760
I have a lot of friends who have
been through the program, so...

14:33.762 --> 14:36.129
They always tell me that
they're uncomfortable...

14:36.131 --> 14:38.564
with people drinking
right in front of them.

14:38.566 --> 14:40.433
So I just... Ah.

14:41.835 --> 14:46.272
I mean, out of respect, I...
I got what you got.

14:46.274 --> 14:50.742
I'm not any sort of authority
on any sort of program.

14:50.744 --> 14:53.212
From my very limited
outside understanding,

14:53.214 --> 14:55.214
for people who have been
in it a while,

14:55.216 --> 14:58.451
you could snort cocaine off the back
of your hand, they'd be all right.

14:58.453 --> 15:00.386
Right. Right. Right.

15:01.554 --> 15:03.556
You know what I would love to do, man?
What's that?

15:03.558 --> 15:07.192
I would love to do a profile on one of
you guys who's doin' a profile on me.

15:07.194 --> 15:09.495
That is interesting. Is
that too pomo and cute?

15:09.497 --> 15:10.996
Maybe for <i> Rolling Stone.</i>

15:10.998 --> 15:14.232
It would be interesting though.
You think?

15:14.234 --> 15:16.602
I'm sorry, man. What's wrong?

15:16.604 --> 15:19.871
It's just you're gonna go back to
New York and sit at your desk...

15:19.873 --> 15:22.708
and shape this thing
however you want.

15:22.710 --> 15:24.876
To me, it's just
extremely disturbing.

15:24.878 --> 15:26.711
Why is it disturbing?

15:26.713 --> 15:30.582
Because I think I would like to shape the
impression of me that's coming across.

15:30.584 --> 15:33.017
I don't even know
if I like you yet.

15:33.019 --> 15:35.420
I'm so nervous about
whether you like me.

15:35.422 --> 15:36.988
Here you go.

15:36.990 --> 15:38.856
Your food will be out soon.
Can I get you anything else?

15:38.858 --> 15:41.326
No, we're fine. Thank you.
Thanks.

15:41.328 --> 15:43.261
Um...

15:43.263 --> 15:45.697
What's this story about
in your mind?

15:45.699 --> 15:47.699
What does Jann want?

15:47.701 --> 15:50.268
Just what it's like to be the most
talked about writer in the country...

15:50.270 --> 15:53.038
or that sort of thing. Right.

15:53.040 --> 15:55.306
Which makes it sound...

15:55.308 --> 15:57.242
How do you learn
to do this stuff?

15:57.244 --> 15:59.944
Do what? The interviewing.

15:59.946 --> 16:02.079
Does one go
to interviewing school?

16:02.081 --> 16:04.549
Yes, I went to eight years
of interviewing school.

16:04.551 --> 16:06.083
So you got a master's? I did.

16:06.085 --> 16:10.588
Um, no. No, I'm... I'm a writer.

16:10.590 --> 16:12.690
Uh, okay. Great. Yeah.

16:12.692 --> 16:15.059
I mean I write fiction
as well. I...

16:16.195 --> 16:17.862
I just had a novel
published actually.

16:17.864 --> 16:20.531
Great. Yeah.

16:20.533 --> 16:22.133
What's... What's that called?

16:22.135 --> 16:24.935
<i>The Art Fair. The Art Fair.
</i> Great.

16:27.506 --> 16:30.975
And I had a collection
published a few years ago, so...

16:30.977 --> 16:32.810
You're, like,
a nervous guy, huh?

16:32.812 --> 16:36.080
No, no. No, I'm okay. How are you?
I... 'Cos I'm terrified.

16:36.082 --> 16:37.981
Are you? Yes. You're
not alone in this.

16:37.983 --> 16:39.550
Okay. We'll do this together.

16:39.552 --> 16:42.185
No, I think it's gonna
be a lot of fun. Yeah.

16:42.187 --> 16:44.687
The thing about the tour
is, yes,

16:44.689 --> 16:47.323
I would like to get laid
off of it a couple of times.

16:47.325 --> 16:49.858
People come up.
They kind of, like, slither up.

16:49.860 --> 16:52.027
And it seems like...
I don't know.

16:52.029 --> 16:54.295
What I want is not to have
to take any action.

16:54.297 --> 16:57.499
What kind of action? I don't
want to have to say, like,

16:57.501 --> 16:59.267
"Do you want to come
back to the hotel?"

16:59.269 --> 17:01.936
I want them to say, "I am
coming back to your hotel."

17:01.938 --> 17:05.473
"Where is your hotel?" That would
be easier for you, wouldn't it?

17:05.474 --> 17:08.509
I can't stand to look like I'm
actively trading off this sexually.

17:08.511 --> 17:10.845
Which, of course,
I'd be happy to do.

17:10.847 --> 17:13.347
I think, in retrospect, I'm
probably very lucky that I didn't.

17:13.348 --> 17:15.049
Lucky? Why?

17:15.050 --> 17:17.617
It just would have made me feel lonely.
You know?

17:17.619 --> 17:19.086
Lonely? How so?

17:19.088 --> 17:21.122
It wouldn't have had
anything to do with me.

17:21.124 --> 17:23.723
I think it would have
been... just...

17:23.726 --> 17:26.425
Your fame? Yeah. Whatever.

17:26.428 --> 17:27.961
Your fame. You can say it.
Fine, fine.

17:27.963 --> 17:30.296
You're famous. Okay, whatever.

17:30.298 --> 17:33.333
You are. Except, though, if they're
responding to your work...

17:33.335 --> 17:34.600
and your work
is really personal,

17:34.602 --> 17:36.969
then reading you is another
way of meeting you.

17:36.971 --> 17:38.870
Isn't that right?

17:38.872 --> 17:40.405
That's so good. Thank you.

17:40.407 --> 17:42.740
This piece will be excellent
if it's mostly you.

17:42.742 --> 17:45.376
Talk all you want, man. Save
me a whole lot of trouble.

17:54.485 --> 17:57.620
Wow! So this is what
a real car feels like.

17:57.622 --> 18:00.656
The one I got is like riding
around on a power lawn mower.

18:00.658 --> 18:02.691
You know?

18:02.693 --> 18:05.327
Do you think being handsome has
anything to do with your success?

18:06.862 --> 18:08.596
- What?
- No, you're photogenic.

18:08.598 --> 18:10.832
You look good in your author's photo.
Come on.

18:10.834 --> 18:15.070
You have to come put me down if
I even start thinking that way.

18:15.072 --> 18:17.572
Thinking what way? What,
about how books are sold?

18:17.574 --> 18:21.276
Like, "Do you want to do
