connecting to a younger reading audience.

35:18.263 --> 35:20.130
Is that what people think?

35:20.133 --> 35:23.000
I don't see many Gen Xers
wearing them. Geez.

35:23.002 --> 35:25.068
I kinda wish you hadn't
brought this up, man.

35:25.070 --> 35:27.738
I'm sorry about that. Why?

35:27.740 --> 35:30.574
Because now I'm worried
it's going to seem intentional.

35:30.576 --> 35:32.643
Like, if I don't wear it,
am I not wearing it...

35:32.645 --> 35:35.712
because I'm bowing to other people's
perception that it's a commercial choice?

35:35.714 --> 35:38.549
Or do I do what I wanna do even though
it's perceived as a commercial choice?

35:38.551 --> 35:41.818
It's like a whole crazy circle
I gotta go around in now.

35:41.820 --> 35:43.753
Come on. Sorry.

35:43.755 --> 35:46.389
When did you start
wearing them?

35:46.391 --> 35:48.991
In Tucson. It was, like,
a hundred degrees all the time.

35:48.993 --> 35:52.628
I would perspire so heavily, drip
into the electric typewriter.

35:52.630 --> 35:55.297
I was nervous I was gonna
give myself a shock.

35:55.299 --> 35:59.435
And then, at some point, I realized
I felt better with them on.

36:00.970 --> 36:03.939
I know that it's a security blanket
for me whenever I feel nervous...

36:03.941 --> 36:07.375
or, like, I gotta
keep myself together.

36:07.377 --> 36:10.045
Makes me feel kind of creepy,
people view it as an affectation...

36:10.047 --> 36:11.279
or a trademark or something.

36:11.281 --> 36:13.147
It's more of a foible,

36:13.149 --> 36:16.251
the recognition of a weakness that I'm
kind of afraid my head is gonna explode.

36:16.253 --> 36:17.785
Right.

36:23.125 --> 36:25.292
Your parents are both academics.
Is that right?

36:26.161 --> 36:28.795
My dad, philosophy.
My mom, English.

36:28.797 --> 36:30.863
So. You?

36:30.865 --> 36:33.466
Me? Yeah.

36:33.468 --> 36:37.203
My dad is in advertising,
and my mom's a painter.

36:37.205 --> 36:40.207
When they split up, I moved
in with her to SoHo,

36:40.209 --> 36:41.541
and my brother
moved in with my dad.

36:41.543 --> 36:43.843
Sounds like
there's a story there.

36:43.845 --> 36:46.646
Oh, there is.
I... I just wrote it.

36:46.648 --> 36:50.417
What was it like, you know, growing
up in a house divided like that?

36:50.419 --> 36:53.787
Hey. Who's interviewing who?

36:57.559 --> 37:00.460
How old were you when you
started writing fiction?

37:00.462 --> 37:02.129
Like, 21. Something like that.

37:02.131 --> 37:03.964
Really? Never before?

37:03.966 --> 37:07.000
I think I started a World War
II novel when I was nine.

37:07.002 --> 37:09.436
Did you? That's very ambitious.
Thank you.

37:09.438 --> 37:12.605
It was so good, some of my best work.
Come on.

37:12.607 --> 37:15.275
It was about people with
hyper developed skills and powers...

37:15.277 --> 37:17.510
going to invade Hitler's bunker.

37:17.512 --> 37:18.878
Very nice.

37:18.880 --> 37:22.315
Then, in college, I wrote a couple
of papers for other people.

37:22.317 --> 37:25.397
Really? People paid you to
write their papers for them?

37:26.453 --> 37:28.854
I wouldn't put it that coarsely.
How would you...

37:28.856 --> 37:32.024
There was a complicated
system of rewards. I see.

37:32.026 --> 37:33.725
I would read two or three
of their papers...

37:33.727 --> 37:35.793
and get a sense of what
their music was like.

37:35.795 --> 37:38.563
At some point, I realized
I'm really good at this.

37:38.565 --> 37:41.165
I'm like a strange kind
of forger.

37:41.167 --> 37:43.200
I can sort of sound
like anybody.

37:43.202 --> 37:46.137
It's kind of scary. Um...

37:46.139 --> 37:48.772
Odds are I'm gonna want
to interview your parents.

37:51.009 --> 37:53.744
What for? Just
biographical stuff.

37:53.746 --> 37:55.345
Right.

37:56.448 --> 37:58.715
I hereby request
that you don't.

37:58.717 --> 38:01.551
Really? They're very
private people.

38:01.553 --> 38:04.922
And so I would have a problem with that.
Mmm, okay.

38:04.924 --> 38:07.124
So, no, you may not.

38:08.260 --> 38:10.861
Okay. I may not.

38:17.835 --> 38:21.338
<i>Now boarding,
Flight 54 to Minneapolis.</i>

38:23.374 --> 38:25.655
Ticket. Thank you.

38:30.614 --> 38:33.216
Crap jobs? Oh, man.

38:33.218 --> 38:37.386
I was a security guard at a software
company for three and a half months.

38:37.388 --> 38:41.557
Really? I walked around in
this polyester uniform...

38:41.559 --> 38:44.427
under these fluorescent
lights, twirling a baton,

38:44.429 --> 38:46.862
checking in on the walkie
every 10 minutes.

38:46.864 --> 38:48.630
"All clear at this cubicle."

38:48.632 --> 38:52.101
It was like every bad '60s novel
about meaningless authority.

38:52.103 --> 38:55.771
You're thinking, "My God, I had two books
come out in my early 20s, and here I am."

38:55.773 --> 38:59.509
No. No, as a matter of fact, one of
the things I liked about that job...

38:59.511 --> 39:01.911
is that I walked around not thinking.
Really?

39:01.913 --> 39:06.616
Mmm, in a very, like, "Huh. A
ceiling tile" sort of way.

39:06.618 --> 39:08.578
And what about after the
security guard thing?

39:08.604 --> 39:09.620
Was there anything else?

39:09.622 --> 39:11.788
Oh, this is the worst. What?

39:11.790 --> 39:13.656
Get this down. I am.

39:13.658 --> 39:16.005
I was a towel boy at
this chichi health club.

39:16.031 --> 39:17.127
You were a towel boy?

39:17.129 --> 39:18.736
I was called something
other than a towel boy.

39:18.762 --> 39:19.796
I was, in effect, a towel boy.

39:19.798 --> 39:22.595
Occasionally trusted
with checking people in.

39:22.621 --> 39:23.567
"Show your ID."

39:23.569 --> 39:25.502
Anyway, one day
I'm sitting there.

39:25.504 --> 39:27.838
Who should walk in to get
their towel but this guy,

39:27.840 --> 39:31.674
this writer that I knew who won a Whiting
writer's award the same year I had.

39:31.676 --> 39:33.176
Oh, God. Yeah.

39:33.178 --> 39:35.578
So there I am.
I'm sitting there.

39:35.580 --> 39:37.780
I'd been on a rostrum with
this guy... Holy shit.

39:37.782 --> 39:40.049
Having Eudora Welty
give us an award.

39:40.051 --> 39:42.117
Two years later,
I'm sitting there...

39:42.119 --> 39:45.354
It's the first time I remember ever
actively diving under something...

39:45.356 --> 39:46.855
to have somebody
avoid seeing me.

39:46.857 --> 39:48.690
You dove under a table?
Something like that.

39:48.692 --> 39:52.361
Did you think you were done? I thought
life was over. I was pretty sure.

39:52.363 --> 39:54.483
And was this after
your suicide watch?

39:57.700 --> 40:01.135
Okay, how do you
know about that?

40:01.137 --> 40:03.738
I... I read about it somewhere.

40:03.740 --> 40:07.007
This was McLean's, right?
How long were you there?

40:07.009 --> 40:10.544
I was there for eight days.
And why were you there?

40:10.546 --> 40:13.680
Because I was probably afraid
that I would do something stupid.

40:13.682 --> 40:15.281
Okay.

40:18.018 --> 40:20.920
I had a friend in high school
who tried to kill himself...

40:20.922 --> 40:23.289
by sitting in a garage
with the car running.

40:23.291 --> 40:25.090
And what it turned out was
he didn't die.

40:25.092 --> 40:27.026
It just really
fucked up his brain.

40:27.028 --> 40:28.994
And I, you know...

40:28.996 --> 40:32.665
I knew that if anyone was fated to
fuck up a suicide attempt, it was me.

40:32.667 --> 40:35.267
So there you are.
You're still in your 20s.

40:35.269 --> 40:37.435
My late 20s.
Okay, your late 20s.

40:37.437 --> 40:39.905
And you're in
some kind of pain...

40:39.907 --> 40:42.841
about your desire to become some
sort of successful literary person.

40:42.843 --> 40:46.478
I think that the not very sophisticated
diagnosis is that I was depressed.

40:47.213 --> 40:48.980
Okay.

40:48.982 --> 40:53.451
Okay. At that point, my ego was
all tied up in my writing.

40:53.453 --> 40:56.221
It's the only thing
that I'd gotten any, like,

40:56.223 --> 40:58.823
food pellets
from the universe for.

40:58.825 --> 41:00.791
And I felt very trapped.

41:00.793 --> 41:03.461
"Oh, my five years are up
and I gotta move on.

41:03.463 --> 41:06.063
I don't want to move on."

41:06.065 --> 41:07.831
And I felt stuck.

41:09.601 --> 41:12.302
And it's not like I felt stuck
because I drank, okay?

41:12.304 --> 41:17.006
It was like I felt
my life was over at 28,

41:17.008 --> 41:19.008
and I felt really bad.

41:20.444 --> 41:23.012
I did not want to feel that,
so I did all sorts of stuff.

41:23.014 --> 41:25.080
I would drink real heavy.

41:25.082 --> 41:28.084
I would... fuck strangers.

41:28.086 --> 41:30.953
Sometimes I would not drink at all,
not drink at all for two weeks.

41:30.955 --> 41:35.090
Instead, I would run 10 miles
every morning in a desperate...

41:37.461 --> 41:40.129
like, a very American...

41:40.131 --> 41:45.068
"I will fix this somehow by taking
radical action" sort of thing.

41:48.338 --> 41:51.107
And here you are promoting
this acclaimed book.

41:51.109 --> 41:52.875
That's not bad.

41:58.348 --> 42:01.383
David, this is nice.

42:01.385 --> 42:03.486
This is not real.

42:12.529 --> 42:14.531
By the way, an escort is
supposed to pick me up...

42:14.533 --> 42:16.966
and escort me to the reading.

42:16.968 --> 42:20.537
Of course, when I hear "escort," I
picture, like, full geisha and hair...

42:20.539 --> 42:22.138
Of course, right.

42:22.140 --> 42:24.907
Take you to the bookstore and
take you back to the hotel,

42:24.909 --> 42:27.911
walk on your back and then
just fuck your eyeballs out.

42:27.913 --> 42:30.680
I think that's her.
Ah, just as I pictured.

42:30.682 --> 42:33.417
Mr. Wallace. Just "Dave."

42:33.419 --> 42:36.253
I recognize you from
your photograph. Okay.

42:36.255 --> 42:37.654
I'm Patty Gundersson.

42:37.656 --> 42:39.723
And welcome to Minneapolis.

42:39.725 --> 42:42.492
Thank you, Patty. Hi. I'm David Lipsky.
How are you?

42:42.494 --> 42:45.229
Hi. Okay. David and David.
That's easy.

42:45.231 --> 42:47.731
- It's the Twin Cities, so...
- Hmm.

42:47.733 --> 42:50.367
We only just met. He's
writing a piece on the tour.

42:50.369 --> 42:54.637
- Should we get going?
- Yes. Come on. Come on. Great.

42:54.639 --> 42:56.573
How's your morning, Patty?
Oh, it's good.

42:56.575 --> 42:58.675
How about you guys?
Was the flight all right?

43:05.283 --> 43:09.619
You would not believe the
famous people I've driven.

43:09.621 --> 43:12.421
Shirley MacLaine when she
was on her book tour.

43:12.423 --> 43:15.291
Ron Wood, you know,
of the Rolling Stones.

43:15.293 --> 43:16.692
Of course. Yeah. Wow.

43:16.694 --> 43:19.728
Peter O'Toole. Oh, my gosh.

43:19.730 --> 43:21.664
Very thin, but delightful.

43:21.666 --> 43:23.532
Hey! Look, there's the
Mary Tyler Moore statue.

43:23.534 --> 43:25.233
Yeah, there it is.

43:25.235 --> 43:26.635
Did you want to stop?

43:26.637 --> 43:28.770
Oh. No, it's fine.

43:28.772 --> 43:30.538
Thank you. Are you sure?

43:30.540 --> 43:33.775
Everybody who comes here, that's
the first thing they want to see.

43:33.777 --> 43:37.078
"Where did Mary Tyler Moore
throw her hat up in the air?"

43:37.080 --> 43:38.780
It's really one of our
biggest attractions.

43:38.782 --> 43:40.681
Are you sure you don't
want me to stop?

43:40.683 --> 43:44.919
Definitely. No.
Thank you though.

43:44.921 --> 43:47.221
Trust me. This is about
as sexy as the tour gets.

43:48.457 --> 43:50.391
Mr... Uh, Lipsky.

43:50.393 --> 43:53.293
L-I-P-S-K-Y.

43:53.295 --> 43:55.328
I've got you
in a standard double.

43:55.330 --> 43:57.864
And Mr. Wallace? Yes.

43:57.866 --> 43:59.866
You have a room with twins.

43:59.868 --> 44:03.169
Ah, yes. Anita and Consuela.

44:04.371 --> 44:05.838
Excuse me?

44:10.143 --> 44:12.377
All right, man. I'll see you soon.
I'm gonna take a nap.

44:12.379 --> 44:14.847
Oh. Uh...

44:16.015 --> 44:17.415
Yeah.

44:17.417 --> 44:19.617
<i>What does he say
about the heroin rumors?</i>

44:19.619 --> 44:21.553
I haven't gotten to that.

44:21.555 --> 44:23.288
<i>What are you waiting for?</i>

44:23.290 --> 44:26.558
What am I supposed to say? "Is it
true you were a heroin addict?"

44:26.560 --> 44:28.660
<i>Yes. That's your story.</i>

44:28.662 --> 44:31.062
Okay, well, that's... It's hard.

44:31.064 --> 44:34.766
<i>Why, because you like him?
</i> Yeah. Yes.

44:34.768 --> 44:37.135
<i>David, you gotta press him.
</i> Okay.

44:37.137 --> 44:39.838
<i>Be a prick if you have to. You're
not his best buddy.</i> I know.

44:39.840 --> 44:42.001
<i>You're a reporter.</i>
All right. Bye.

44:52.884 --> 44:54.784
It's right up here.

44:57.488 --> 44:59.087
Ready?

45:01.891 --> 45:04.692
- Ah!
- There he is.

45:04.694 --> 45:05.926
I can't believe
you guys actually came.

45:05.928 --> 45:08.229
Yeah, of course. Hi. Hi.

45:08.231 --> 45:09.964
Wouldn't miss it. Hello.

45:09.966 --> 45:12.499
Gluttons for punishment, both of you.
I know.

45:12.501 --> 45:16.370
Uh, this is Dave Lipsky. He's a
reporter from <i> Rolling Stone.</i>

45:16.372 --> 45:18.205
Yes. Hi. Oh.

45:18.207 --> 45:20.274
This is Julie. Hi. Nice
to meet you, Julie.

45:20.276 --> 45:22.142
Great to meet you.

45:22.144 --> 45:23.743
And, uh... This is Betsy.

45:23.745 --> 45:25.578
Betsy and I went
to grad school together.

45:25.580 --> 45:27.547
How nice. Nice to
meet you, Betsy.

45:27.549 --> 45:29.282
And, Julie, how do you...

45:29.284 --> 45:31.818
Julie... Here, turn this on.
This is on, right?

45:31.820 --> 45:33.686
It is. Why? Go ahead.
Do you wanna...

45:33.688 --> 45:36.422
I'll do it. Julie wrote
me a fan letter.

45:36.424 --> 45:37.891
Really? Mm-hmm.

45:37.893 --> 45:40.326
I really did. I... Yeah.

45:40.328 --> 45:43.228
I was the books editor at <i> City
Pages,</i> and I wrote him a fan letter.

45:43.230 --> 45:45.364
Julie's worked with
a whole lot of writers.

45:45.366 --> 45:47.632
So I was very discriminating.

45:47.634 --> 45:50.402
And then it turned out that we
actually like each other as people.

45:50.404 --> 45:53.271
Indeed. That's actually what
happened with Jon Franzen and me.

45:53.273 --> 45:56.174
I wrote him a fan letter. Turns
out writers are real pushovers...

45:56.176 --> 45:57.875
when it comes to flattery.

45:57.877 --> 45:59.476
So you could try that sometime.

45:59.478 --> 46:01.712
I got it. Very subtle.

46:01.714 --> 46:05.115
Friends of friends who
have friends, as well,

46:05.117 --> 46:06.983
who actually know who... Cookies?

46:06.985 --> 46:09.553
Oh, no. Thanks a lot.
Oh, no. Thank you.

46:09.555 --> 46:10.954
Cookies?

46:10.956 --> 46:14.391
Really? Yes, and I've actually
been sworn to secrecy.

46:14.393 --> 46:17.593
Are you sure I can't get
you something to drink?

46:18.595 --> 46:20.697
Do you have any artificial spit?

46:20.699 --> 46:23.866
I don't know why
you guys are laughing.

46:23.868 --> 46:25.969
It's an actual
pharmaceutical product.

46:25.971 --> 46:28.638
Called Xero-Lube. It's
like artificial saliva?

46:28.640 --> 46:30.306
That's right. That's right, David.
Really?

46:30.308 --> 46:32.942
Except it's better because
it actually lubricates.

46:32.944 --> 46:35.244
You don't get that, like...

46:35.246 --> 46:37.112
I see. That clicky sound.

46:37.114 --> 46:39.315
Could you do that for <i> Rolling Stone?
</i> Here you go.

46:39.317 --> 46:42.217
I'll have to remember that.

46:42.219 --> 46:45.054
It's all right. Next tour,
I'll bring myself a case.

46:45.056 --> 46:47.456
In the meantime,
what can I get you?

46:47.458 --> 46:49.157
Just water with no ice, please.

46:49.159 --> 46:52.895
Are you a fiction wri... This
is off the record. Oh, good.

46:52.897 --> 46:55.230
Are you a fiction writer?
I'm a poet actually.

46:55.232 --> 46:58.400
Really? Could I have
seen anything of yours?

46:58.402 --> 47:00.835
I just had my first poem
published in <i> The Kenyon Review.</i>

47:00.837 --> 47:04.539
Really? Wow. Congratulations.
Yes. Thank you.

47:08.877 --> 47:11.144
I'm sorry. I don't mean
to be a prima donna,

47:11.146 --> 47:13.513
but do you mind if we
don't do a Q and A?

47:13.515 --> 47:16.583
Yeah, of course. Whatever makes
you feel most comfortable.

47:16.585 --> 47:18.117
Thank you. Sure.

47:18.119 --> 47:21.287
It's always questions like,
"Where do you get your ideas?"

47:21.289 --> 47:25.089
I don't know. From a Time-Life
subscription series for 17.95 a month.

47:25.091 --> 47:27.992
Okay. Now, it's show time.
Okay.

47:29.461 --> 47:31.328
Here we go. Yeah.

47:31.330 --> 47:33.631
It's all downhill from here.
It's fine.

47:33.633 --> 47:37.167
This is the very last stop
on his book tour,

47:37.169 --> 47:39.436
and we're very lucky
to get him.

47:39.438 --> 47:42.372
Ladies and gentlemen,
welcome to The Hungry Mind,

47:42.374 --> 47:44.308
David Foster Wallace.

47:52.818 --> 47:55.921
Hello. Hi. Hi.

47:55.923 --> 47:57.889
No, I never show
my mother anything.

47:57.891 --> 47:59.690
Now I feel embarrassed
that I said that.

47:59.692 --> 48:01.759
But that's very sweet.
It is, right?

48:01.761 --> 48:03.794
What's that supposed
to be, a computer?

48:03.796 --> 48:06.963
No, that's a smiley face.
Oh. Right.

48:06.965 --> 48:08.699
I could put white-out
on it if you want.

48:08.701 --> 48:11.434
That's okay. It's your book.
Okay.

48:12.869 --> 48:15.972
Oh, man. This old thing.
Do you mind?

48:15.974 --> 48:18.441
I don't mind, but the
new one's a lot better.

48:19.276 --> 48:20.410
Awesome.

48:20.412 --> 48:23.812
I just realized that they...
they want me to be good.

48:24.613 --> 48:26.414
You know what I mean?

48:26.416 --> 48:29.383
It's just something about,
like, giving back.

48:29.385 --> 48:31.017
You know, in that way.

48:31.019 --> 48:33.820
That made me feel kind of
better about everything.

48:33.822 --> 48:36.656
Please, give us the... It's
not... There's no story.

48:36.658 --> 48:39.693
How did it happen then? Okay.

48:39.695 --> 48:41.327
I couldn't be regular
old Dave Wallace...

48:41.329 --> 48:43.429
'cause there were Dave
Wallaces all over the place.

48:43.431 --> 48:45.490
And David Rains Wallace
wrote for the New Yorker.

48:45.516 --> 48:46.766
I don't know if you remember.

48:46.768 --> 48:49.135
So then, one day... It
was Fred Hill asked me,

48:49.137 --> 48:52.572
"What's your middle name?" Dave
Foster Wallace. That's it.

48:52.574 --> 48:54.440
That's your story? Yes.

48:54.442 --> 48:56.976
That is literally the worst superhero
origin story I've ever heard.

48:56.978 --> 48:59.611
I cannot claim that it
was an origin story.

48:59.613 --> 49:03.248
Dave, remember in Tucson that professor
you kind of locked horns with?

49:03.250 --> 49:06.484
Oh, man. My nemesis, who shall
remain nameless. Oh, come on.

49:06.486 --> 49:09.330
I was just kind of a prick.
I think he was too.

49:09.356 --> 49:10.455
I was unteachable.

49:10.457 --> 49:13.459
I don't think I was actively
unpleasant in class.

49:13.461 --> 49:15.527
You were pretty unpleasant.

49:15.529 --> 49:17.061
Okay, Betsy. Betsy. Really.

49:17.063 --> 49:19.096
Oh, I loved it. I loved it.

49:19.098 --> 49:22.033
Betsy, this is... She loved it.

49:22.035 --> 49:24.001
He was pleasantly unpleasant.

49:24.003 --> 49:26.637
That's a great quote, if you
want to quote something.

49:26.639 --> 49:28.805
I'm gonna have to interview
the teacher as well though.

49:28.807 --> 49:31.775
Hmm.

49:31.777 --> 49:34.944
I have to be up unconscionably early
for this public radio interview,

49:34.946 --> 49:36.078
so we should probably
get going.

49:36.080 --> 49:37.847
That means I have
to get up early too.

